<p><b>Donald Clarence Judd</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1928-06-03"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-03"><a href="/wiki/June_3" title="June 3">June 3</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1928" title="1928">1928</a></span> - <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1994-02-12"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-12"><a href="/wiki/February_12" title="February 12">February 12</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1994" title="1994">1994</a></span>) was a <a href="/wiki/Minimalism" title="Minimalism">minimalist</a> <a href="/wiki/Artist" title="Artist">artist</a> (a term he stridently disavowed).<sup id="cite_ref-tate_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tate-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> In his work, Judd sought autonomy and clarity for the constructed object and the space created by it, ultimately achieving a rigorously democratic presentation without compositional hierarchy. It created an outpouring of seemingly effervescent structure without the rigor associated with minimalism proper.</p>
